# ⚠️ Warning: "w" Mode

If you open an important file like `data.txt` in `"w"` mode, C will **erase everything** in it immediately!

> Always check if the pointer is valid before using it.

```c
if (fptr == NULL) {
    printf("Error opening file!");
    exit(1);
}
```

# Storing Text ✍️

Use `fprintf()` just like `printf()`, but with the file pointer as the first argument.

```c
FILE *fp = fopen("notes.txt", "w");

fprintf(fp, "Hello File!\n");
fprintf(fp, "Score: %d\n", 100);

fclose(fp); // Always close!
```
You can also use `fputc('A', fp)` to write a single character.

# Retrieving Data 📖

Use `fscanf()` or `fgets()`.

```c
FILE *fp = fopen("notes.txt", "r");
char buffer[100];

// Reads one word (stops at space)
fscanf(fp, "%s", buffer);

// Reads a whole line
fgets(buffer, 100, fp);
```

Reading ends when `EOF` (End of File) is reached.

# File Logger Demo

